defaultDr Worthy:default You have Rufus Pollock from the Open Knowledge Foundation 
defaultspeaking 
defaultlater.  
defaultIt has 
defaulta very good definition of open data: information that is reusable
default and accessible to all, 
defaultand can be read by a machine.  That is a very simple definition.  Helen is exactly right in what she says.  T
defaulthe problem is that it is conflated with lots of other ideas
default and there 
defaultis an assumption that open data means open government, for example.  
defaultThere are quite a lot of assumptions built into an idea like 
defaultthat—
defaultthat open data then automatically leads to transparency and accountability of 
defaultg
defaultovernment.  
defaultQ3 default&#xa0; 
defaultChairdefault:default What is the difference between open data and open government?  
defaultDr Worthy:default 
defaultOpen 
defaultdata is about technology and
default making something machine
default&#x2011;
defaultreadable.  Open 
defaultgovernment brings in more political ideas about making government accountable and answerable.  
defaultFor example, 
defaultf
defaultreedom of 
defaulti
defaultnformation is about accessing information.  Open data is about re-using information and doing interesting and new things with it to gain new understandings.  
defaultThere is considerable overlap there, but they are not necessarily the same thing
default, not least because the Government can control what open data is given out.  
defaultQ4 default&#xa0; 
defaultChairdefault:default How well does each of you think the Government understands this?  
defaultProfessor Margetts:default Not very well.  
defaultQ5 default&#xa0; 
defaultChairdefault:default 
defaultThank you.  
defaultWhy was that so hard to say?  
defaultProfessor Margetts:default 
defaultFor the reason I 
defaultgave
default.  To criticise open data is a bit like saying you do not like babies: you are not supposed to say it.  It is true that it has very noble aims
default,
default and most of the people who are great advocates of open data have the three noble aims that I mentioned.  The point is that there is an idea that open data will somehow automatically lead to open government
default,
default and that is by no means the case.  
